model_explanation: "only gave Ellen GRAPES" means grapes and nothing else. The statement that Sam also gave Ellen oranges contradicts that exclusivity.

the focus is on who received apples. S1 says that Sam only gave apples to Ellen, not that apples were the only thing given. S2 talks about Rob receiving apples, which is a separate event and does not contradict that Ellen was the sole apples recipient in one context.
if Sam only gave Mary oranges, it means no other fruits were given to her. Therefore, it directly follows that Sam didn’t give Mary bananas.

the prosodic focus is on Mary receiving oranges exclusively, meaning Mary got no other fruit. This doesn’t exclude Sam from giving the same fruit to someone else like Tom. The two pieces of information are independent.

the focus is on Mary being the exclusive recipient of oranges in the original statement. It does not speak to whether or not Tom got them as well. Thus, the statements don’t relate directly to each other—Tom isn’t mentioned in S1 at all—so they are independent.
if Sam only gave Mary grapes, it means no apples were given. Stating that Sam also gave Mary apples contradicts this.
the statement focuses on Sue being the sole recipient of apples. If Sam also gave apples to Mary, that contradicts the idea that Sue was the exclusive recipient.
if Sam only gave Bill oranges, it implies Bill got no other fruit. Saying Sam gave Bill bananas contradicts that exclusive claim.
if Ellen only received bananas, it excludes any other fruit. The claim that Sam also gave Ellen grapes directly contradicts that.
if Tom only got bananas, it follows that he didn’t receive any oranges. This is entailed by the exclusivity of "only bananas."
